        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p><strong>Theorem 1</strong> : Suppose $K$ and $C$ are subsets of a topological vector space $X$,  $K$ is compact, $C$ is closed, and $K \cap C = \emptyset$. Then $0$ has a neighbhorhood $V$ such that</p><script type="math/tex; mode=display">\begin{aligned}(K + V) \cap (C + V) = \emptyset\end{aligned}</script><p><strong>Propositon</strong>: If $W$ is a neighborhood of 0 in $X$, then there is a neighborhood $U$ of 0 which is symmetric (in the case that $U = -U$) and which satisfies $U + U \subseteq W$.<br><a id="more"></a></p><hr>]]></content>
      
      
